# Copying, Yanking and Registers 

#Example Vim's registers are must more elaborate than the standard clipboard
# available on your standard OS
# Whenever you delete, change, search, substitute, or yank text 
# vim stores it in a register
# The register we have been using up to now is the default regiser
# There are 8 types of register
# 48 total registers
# You may delete, change, substitute, search or yank to any register

# CHOOSE A REGISTER WITH A DOUBLE QUOTATION MARK
# To yank a link into the register called a, type:
"ayy
#Break it down
"a								# Use regiser a
yy								# Yank (copy) current line

"ap								# paste from resister a

# Named registers
"a-z
"A-Z 
#Uppercase registers append new text to their contexts 
"" 								# The unnamed register. Contains the last deleted text

# Whenever you delete text with 'd','c', 's' or 'x', or copy it with 'y', 

# Numbered registes 1-9 always contain the text from the last delete
# or change command, but you'll rarely use them. 

:registers				# show content of all registers

"+ 								# System clipboard

# You can repeat your last change or yank with '.'
# and you may specify a different count if you want ('2.') 

@: 								# Repeat the last COMMAND LINE COMMAND
#Break it down
@									# Exectute text as command
: 								# Use the : register as the text of the command

# Macros
#An example
qadWWPjp
# /Stop recording with q
qa								Start a recording named a
dW								# Delete a word
w									# go forward one word
p									# paste contents
j									# move down one line
q									# quit recoring

@a								# Execute a macro called a
5@a								# Do five times

# Plugins
# Vim can be extended with plugins, which are just vim scripts loaded automatically
# There are two types of plugins
global						# Used for all
filetype					# Specific to a particular type of file 

# Almost all vim plugins are releases in script section of 
# vim.org
# Most plugins are zip files which you unzip in your .vim dir
# Pathogen makes things easier
# Unzip to .vim/bundle directory
# Check out Tim Pope's plugins (author of 'pathogen',
# and many others)

